    <chapter xml:id="ch-Vectors-and-the-Geometry-of-Space">
      <title>Vectors and the Geometry of Space</title>
      <introduction>
      <p>
      Vector calculus is the branch of mathematics that deals with vector fields and their derivatives. 
      It is essential for understanding the behavior of physical systems in three-dimensional space.
      </p>
      <p>
      In this chapter, we will explore the fundamental concepts of vector calculus, including gradient, divergence, and curl.
      </p>
      </introduction>
      <xi:include href="./notes/2DVectors.ptx" />
      <xi:include href="./notes/3DVectors.ptx" />
      <xi:include href="./notes/Dot.ptx" />
      <xi:include href="./notes/Cross.ptx" />
      <xi:include href="./notes/Planes.ptx" />
      <xi:include href="./notes/Surfaces.ptx" />

   </chapter>

  <chapter xml:id="ch-Vector-valued-functions">
      <title>Vector-valued Functions</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Vector-valued functions are functions that take one or more variables and return a vector. 
          They are used to describe curves and surfaces in three-dimensional space.
        </p>
        <p>
          In this chapter, we will study the properties of vector-valued functions, including limits, continuity, and differentiability.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <xi:include href="./notes/Vector-valued-functions.ptx" />
      <xi:include href="./notes/Derivatives-of-vector-functions.ptx" />

    </chapter>


